That's not true. But synthetic lethality opportunities for tumors

26
00:01:25.100 --> 00:01:28.560
with MMEJ deficiency, that's microhomology-mediated

27
00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:30.720
end joining deficiency.

28
00:01:31.980 --> 00:01:35.920
Okay. So, as everyone knows, there are at least six

29
00:01:35.980 --> 00:01:38.360
major DNA repair pathways in human cells.

30
00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:41.860
These have various names: base excision repair, nucleotide excision repair,

31
00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:44.290
mismatch repair, homologous recombination.

32
00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:47.970
Actually, the Fanconi pathway, which my lab works on very closely, is part of

33
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.360
homologous recombination, NHEJ and TLS.

34
00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:52.140
Now,

35
00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:56.980
normal human cells have these six DNA repair pathways

36
00:01:57.640 --> 00:02:00.000
to varying degrees depending on the cell type.

37
00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:04.460
But cancer cells are often missing one of these DNA repair pathways.

38
00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:08.280
And this is interesting. This gives an advantage to the cancer, if you

39
00:02:08.380 --> 00:02:12.360
will, because of this DNA repair deficiency, the cancer can now break and reform

40
00:02:12.380 --> 00:02:16.280
chromosomes, generate mutations, knock out p53, and do all the

41
00:02:16.340 --> 00:02:20.280
things that cancers like to do. But it's a vulnerability to this cancer

42
00:02:20.340 --> 00:02:23.540
as well, because by knocking out that DNA repair pathway,

43
00:02:24.630 --> 00:02:28.460
these cancer cells are sensitive to radiation and chemotherapy often.

44
00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:30.000
So for instance,

45
00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:34.700
an example of this is some bladder cancers are deficient in nucleotide

46
00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:37.860
excision repair, and those tumors respond better to cisplatin.

47
00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:38.920
That's one example.

48
00:02:39.820 --> 00:02:42.840
Okay. But this is about synthetic lethality, this session.

49
00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:45.680
Some cancers, when they knock out one pathway,

50
00:02:46.620 --> 00:02:50.560
they become hyper-dependent on another pathway, this big arrow here, and that's

51
00:02:50.580 --> 00:02:54.540
an opportunity for us as targeted therapy scientists and doctors.

52
00:02:55.410 --> 00:02:59.000
If you could develop a drug against this hyperactive therapy like a PARP

53
00:02:59.040 --> 00:03:02.230
inhibitor in a BRCA deficient cell, you can have a way of

54
00:03:02.440 --> 00:03:04.120
monotherapy for developing the drug.

55
00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:07.620
Okay, so this is a principle of synthetic lethality, as I like to

56
00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:11.049
say. All right, so these are the two pathways which I'm going to focus on,

57
00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:14.180
homologous recombination on the left and

58
00:03:14.520 --> 00:03:16.920
microhomology-mediated end joining on the right.

59
00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:20.780
These are two very important pathways which regulate or repair a

60
00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:22.640
double-strand break at the top of the slide.

61
00:03:23.420 --> 00:03:26.820
So homologous recombination is an error-free pathway. Okay?

62
00:03:27.780 --> 00:03:31.690
It uses BRCA1 and BRCA2 and PALB2 and

63
00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:34.260
RAD51C proteins that you all know about

64
00:03:35.060 --> 00:03:38.440
and performs error-free repair during S-phase.

65
00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:43.120
MMEJ is very different. It's a very efficient DNA repair pathway, but

66
00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:45.260
it's maybe utilized less.

67
00:03:46.440 --> 00:03:50.240
It's the same principle that double-strand break is resected a little bit and

68
00:03:50.300 --> 00:03:54.120
then a very important polymerase called Pol Q or Pol

69
00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:58.060
theta, which is one of the 15 human DNA polymerases, plays a major

70
00:03:58.100 --> 00:03:59.400
role here in MMEJ.

71
00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:04.220
And other enzymes like PARP and FEN1, APEX 2 play a role in this

72
00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:07.280
pathway as well. This is an error-prone pathway.

73
00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:11.240
When this pathway is used, there are indels, insertions and

74
00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:15.080
deletions, and point mutations, mutations that you often see in signature three

75
00:04:15.260 --> 00:04:18.601
in a BRCA deficient tumor occurs in mitosis.

76
00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:21.140
Now, we all know this, right?

77
00:04:22.041 --> 00:04:25.760
When a tumor has a deficiency in homologous recombination, BRCA1 or

78
00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:29.380
BRCA2 is mutated, say breast, ovarian, prostate, pancreatic

79
00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:30.840
cancers with BRCA mutations.

80
00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:35.560
Those tumors deficient in HR now upregulate.

81
00:04:35.680 --> 00:04:39.440
They upregulate MMEJ, so there's an increase in expression of Pol

82
00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:43.240
Q. It's one of the reasons that Pol Q inhibitors are under investigation right

83
00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:45.640
now in collaboration with PARP inhibitors.

84
00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:50.300
And now with this upregulation of MMEJ, there's an increase in point

85
00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:54.170
mutagenesis, as I said. So the question for today is the

86
00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:58.240
opposite. Could we find a tumor or tumors which are deficient

87
00:04:58.280 --> 00:05:01.720
in MMEJ at baseline, a defect in Pol theta?

88
00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:06.100
And we would expect that those tumors, because of a defect in Pol theta

89
00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:09.880
and MMEJ, that they would have a hyperactive homologous

90
00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:13.490
recombination pathway and might be sensitive to drugs which

91
00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:17.159
inhibit homologous recombination. Interesting hypothesis.

92
00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:21.560
Okay, so the answer is yes, we found such a tumor, and that tumor is a

93
00:05:21.580 --> 00:05:24.940
Ewing sarcoma. But now we're finding more tumors that have defects in

94
00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:28.000
MMEJ. But Ewing sarcoma is going to be the example.

95
00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:31.580
So how did we find this? So we went to this very important paper from Nature back

96
00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:35.290
in 2013 that looked at mutations in human

97
00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:39.280
tumors across the spectrum. And of course, you find at the far right,

98
00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:43.090
melanomas have lots of point mutations, lots of neoantigens, maybe one of the

99
00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:45.480
reasons immunotherapy is so effective there.

100
00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:48.820
Other tumors kind of in the middle of this graph, like ovarian and

101
00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:52.280
prostate, pancreatic cancer, they have some

102
00:05:52.900 --> 00:05:56.660
increased mutagenesis. But at the far left here, these are interesting

103
00:05:56.760 --> 00:06:00.590
tumors. Rhabdoid tumors and Ewing tumors and

104
00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:03.536
thyroid tumors. These tumors have very low-...

105
00:06:03.556 --> 00:06:07.196
point mutation frequency and very low,

106
00:06:07.956 --> 00:06:11.536
so if you do a mutational signature on these tumors, you find very few mutations,

107
00:06:12.536 --> 00:06:15.916
and you find a low level of insertions and deletions.

108
00:06:15.976 --> 00:06:19.596
So they said to us, "Maybe these tumors have a defect in MMEJ." That was the

109
00:06:19.616 --> 00:06:22.936
hypothesis. Okay, so Ewing sarcoma.

110
00:06:24.416 --> 00:06:28.176
It's a rare cancer. It's the second most common cancer in bone in children.

111
00:06:28.896 --> 00:06:32.156
Results from a chromosome 1122 translocation.

112
00:06:32.996 --> 00:06:36.716
Metastatic disease is quite difficult to treat, a 30%

113
00:06:36.816 --> 00:06:37.676
five-year survival.

114
00:06:38.536 --> 00:06:42.076
These tumors are quite sensitive to DNA-damaging agents, so radiation and

115
00:06:42.096 --> 00:06:42.776
chemotherapy.

116
00:06:43.656 --> 00:06:47.276
High doses, actually. It's a very difficult clinical course for these

117
00:06:47.596 --> 00:06:49.016
young people with Ewing sarcoma.

118
00:06:50.166 --> 00:06:53.836
The tumor is driven by this EWS-FLI1 fusion

119
00:06:53.896 --> 00:06:57.036
protein, shown on the right here. This fusion protein

120
00:06:57.996 --> 00:07:01.636
has EWSR1 at the amino terminus. That's a splicing factor.

121
00:07:02.076 --> 00:07:05.496
Okay? And FLI1 at the carboxy terminus, that's a

122
00:07:05.556 --> 00:07:09.436
transcriptional activator. And there have been some really elegant studies

123
00:07:09.476 --> 00:07:12.976
done with the EWS-FLI1 showing it has

124
00:07:13.036 --> 00:07:14.796
increased transcriptional activity,

125
00:07:16.136 --> 00:07:18.576
and maybe that's driving the cancer development.

126
00:07:19.096 --> 00:07:21.996
But fewer studies have been done on the splicing element, and what I'm going to

127
00:07:22.076 --> 00:07:25.756
show you is that this fusion protein, EWS-FLI1, inhibits

128
00:07:25.836 --> 00:07:29.436
splicing of the Pol theta Polq messenger

129
00:07:29.496 --> 00:07:29.936
RNA.

130
00:07:31.296 --> 00:07:35.046
Okay, so by DepMap analysis, indeed, if you knock out

131
00:07:35.176 --> 00:07:38.936
Polq or if you knock out EWSR1, you can

132
00:07:38.996 --> 00:07:42.056
kill BRCA2-deficient, HR-deficient tumor cells.

133
00:07:42.096 --> 00:07:45.566
So DepMap really showed that, yeah, EWSR1 looks like it's

134
00:07:46.636 --> 00:07:50.356
required for MMEJ, just like Polq is

135
00:07:50.396 --> 00:07:54.336
required. And EWS completion results in loss of

136
00:07:54.386 --> 00:07:55.416
the Polq protein.

137
00:07:56.336 --> 00:08:00.156
Okay? And then you could actually look at this more closely, and you could knock

138
00:08:00.296 --> 00:08:04.176
down EWSR1, the splicing factor. That

139
00:08:04.256 --> 00:08:07.436
disrupts, that lowers DNA repair by

140
00:08:07.496 --> 00:08:08.896
microhomology-mediated end joining.

141
00:08:09.136 --> 00:08:12.736
But you could replace this with Pol theta, put Polq

142
00:08:13.036 --> 00:08:16.886
back in, and now you restore MMEJ. So clearly, it was showing

143
00:08:16.916 --> 00:08:20.466
that this fusion, this EWSR1 splicing factor, was

144
00:08:20.516 --> 00:08:23.836
somehow strongly regulating the expression of Polq.

145
00:08:24.696 --> 00:08:25.716
So how does it do this?

146
00:08:26.616 --> 00:08:29.776
So it does it through splicing. So it turns out, if you knock out

147
00:08:29.816 --> 00:08:30.826
EWSR1,

148
00:08:32.016 --> 00:08:35.576
shown here on the left, in a RPE cell, or retinal

149
00:08:35.596 --> 00:08:39.456
pigment cell, a normal cell if you will, you

150
00:08:39.516 --> 00:08:42.677
get an increase in splicing defects.

151
00:08:42.896 --> 00:08:46.376
So if you knock out EWSR1, you get exon 25

152
00:08:46.436 --> 00:08:49.816
skipping, very important exon in the Polq messenger RNA,

153
00:08:50.776 --> 00:08:52.756
and now the protein is not expressed.

154
00:08:53.456 --> 00:08:53.616
So

155
00:08:54.736 --> 00:08:57.856
exon 25 skipping, caused by a loss of

156
00:08:57.896 --> 00:09:01.276
EWSR1 or by the expression of the fusion

157
00:09:01.316 --> 00:09:05.136
oncoprotein, results in a disruption of splicing and

158
00:09:05.196 --> 00:09:08.696
now skipping of exon 25 of Polq messenger RNA.

159
00:09:09.216 --> 00:09:11.056
We then confirmed this with tumor samples.

160
00:09:11.116 --> 00:09:14.716
So in collaboration with Riaz Gilani and Eli Van Allen,

161
00:09:14.976 --> 00:09:17.166
and some samples collected, actually through a collaboration with

162
00:09:18.136 --> 00:09:18.956
St. Jude as well,

163
00:09:19.876 --> 00:09:21.976
36 Ewing sarcomas were evaluated.

164
00:09:22.066 --> 00:09:26.036
And actually, exon 25 skipping was a common event in those tumors, and

165
00:09:26.096 --> 00:09:29.816
Polq expression was low, suggesting that this was not just an

166
00:09:29.876 --> 00:09:33.466
artifact of cell line study, that in fact, this decrease in

167
00:09:33.496 --> 00:09:37.376
Polq was, in fact, a

168
00:09:37.416 --> 00:09:38.656
reality in these tumors.

169
00:09:39.556 --> 00:09:41.556
Okay, so we wanted to study this more closely then.

170
00:09:41.616 --> 00:09:44.906
How does this splicing factor, EWSR1,

171
00:09:45.616 --> 00:09:49.436
regulate Polq expression? So here's the EWSR1

172
00:09:49.476 --> 00:09:52.316
protein at the top schematically. This is an interesting protein.

173
00:09:52.356 --> 00:09:55.686
It's an RNA-binding protein, like a splicing factor, but it has this

174
00:09:55.736 --> 00:09:59.356
N-terminal region, which is a prion-like domain. Okay?

175
00:10:00.136 --> 00:10:04.016
Now, if you look on the right, if you knock out EWSR1, you get

176
00:10:04.056 --> 00:10:07.396
no Polq expression, lane two. Put the

177
00:10:07.496 --> 00:10:11.256
wild-type EWSR1 splicing factor back in, you restore Polq

178
00:10:11.276 --> 00:10:14.736
expression. But put in the mutant, and you fail to restore.

179
00:10:15.096 --> 00:10:18.976
So there's something about wild-type EWSR1, this full-length protein,

180
00:10:19.716 --> 00:10:23.156
with its prion-like domain, has the ability to properly

181
00:10:23.276 --> 00:10:26.376
splice the messenger RNA for Polq, this

182
00:10:26.416 --> 00:10:30.296
important DNA repair enzyme. So how does this work?

183
00:10:30.916 --> 00:10:33.056
So I'm going to give you the answer first, okay?

184
00:10:33.676 --> 00:10:36.516
Because it's a short talk, but I wanted to sort of get the answer out there and

185
00:10:36.536 --> 00:10:39.196
then show you a little bit about how we came up with this conclusion.

186
00:10:39.956 --> 00:10:42.616
So it turns out that EWSR1, this splicing

187
00:10:42.696 --> 00:10:44.336
factor,

188
00:10:45.196 --> 00:10:49.056
when you immunoprecipitate this protein, it co-precipitates

189
00:10:49.096 --> 00:10:52.386
with two other splicing factors, FKBP1 and

190
00:10:52.476 --> 00:10:56.196
KHSRP, and these splicing factors come together as a

191
00:10:56.216 --> 00:10:59.476
complex, all bound together by these prion-like domains.

192
00:10:59.896 --> 00:11:03.856
And this complex now binds directly to a sequence in

193
00:11:03.916 --> 00:11:07.196
exon 25 of the Polq messenger RNA, and it

194
00:11:07.356 --> 00:11:10.756
stabilizes this exon. So if you knock out this

195
00:11:10.816 --> 00:11:14.556
complex, knocking out EWSR1, or if you

196
00:11:14.596 --> 00:11:17.356
express the fusion protein like the tumor does,

197
00:11:18.436 --> 00:11:21.476
now this exon is not stabilized anymore.

198
00:11:21.996 --> 00:11:25.956
Exon 25 is skipped, and now the cells do not express the Polq

199
00:11:25.966 --> 00:11:29.936
protein, and the cells have a MMEJ DNA repair

200
00:11:30.016 --> 00:11:33.496
deficiency. So that's the answer, and let me tell you how we sort of got to

201
00:11:33.576 --> 00:11:34.656
that.

202
00:11:35.896 --> 00:11:39.676
It turns out that these three proteins, EWSR1 and these two other splicing

203
00:11:39.736 --> 00:11:43.546
factors, form a condensate, and this condensate has the ability now

204
00:11:43.596 --> 00:11:46.816
to act as a splicing condensate and to

205
00:11:47.416 --> 00:11:51.196
stabilize the exon 25 of the

206
00:11:52.096 --> 00:11:53.496
Polq messenger RNA.

207
00:11:54.316 --> 00:11:57.676
And you can see here that if you knock out this splicing

208
00:11:57.836 --> 00:12:01.736
complex, EWSR1 with these two binding factors, now

209
00:12:01.796 --> 00:12:05.736
you cannot form the condensate. You cannot stabilize exon

210
00:12:05.896 --> 00:12:09.304
25.And as a result, the exon is skipped

211
00:12:09.784 --> 00:12:13.304
and POLQ protein drops, and there's no MMEJ.

212
00:12:13.644 --> 00:12:17.564
And the early data really suggests that this is a regulated phenomenon, that in a

213
00:12:17.604 --> 00:12:20.984
cell, depending on DNA damage state, you could either

214
00:12:21.104 --> 00:12:24.784
stabilize this exon or destabilize this

215
00:12:24.844 --> 00:12:27.384
exon and regulate the level of POLQ expression.

216
00:12:28.164 --> 00:12:30.064
Okay, so how does this really work?

217
00:12:30.104 --> 00:12:32.504
How does this condensate stabilize exon 25?

218
00:12:33.224 --> 00:12:34.244
What we did here is we

219
00:12:35.344 --> 00:12:38.444
narrowed it down, we being two very talented postdocs in the lab,

220
00:12:39.364 --> 00:12:42.844
Shuhei Asada and Guangli Xu. What they did is they

221
00:12:43.024 --> 00:12:46.824
found a sequence, a six-base sequence

222
00:12:47.064 --> 00:12:50.864
in the exon of this POLQ messenger RNA, and

223
00:12:50.964 --> 00:12:54.084
this base pair sequence is the binding site for

224
00:12:54.144 --> 00:12:58.064
EWSR1 and this splicing complex. And if you

225
00:12:58.144 --> 00:12:58.924
mutate this

226
00:13:00.224 --> 00:13:04.024
site in messenger RNA, remember, this is an exon, this is a

227
00:13:04.124 --> 00:13:08.084
coding region. You could actually mutate this site but preserve

228
00:13:08.124 --> 00:13:09.424
the amino acid sequence.

229
00:13:10.484 --> 00:13:13.984
That mutation, though, in that site disrupts the binding of the

230
00:13:14.024 --> 00:13:17.744
EWSR1 complex, and you get an exon-skipping event.

231
00:13:18.384 --> 00:13:20.584
And they did this in a very interesting way.

232
00:13:20.644 --> 00:13:24.344
This is a method which has been described where you take a

233
00:13:24.464 --> 00:13:27.604
guide RNA, which is directed against this sequence

234
00:13:28.704 --> 00:13:30.004
in exon 25.

235
00:13:31.264 --> 00:13:32.784
And with that guide RNA, now you

236
00:13:33.744 --> 00:13:37.544
introduce a Cas13, which is a modified

237
00:13:37.584 --> 00:13:40.084
Cas9, which is catalytically inactive.

238
00:13:40.624 --> 00:13:44.484
And that Cas13 now binds to the siRNA at

239
00:13:44.524 --> 00:13:47.904
this site in the exon. And when it does that, it

240
00:13:50.044 --> 00:13:53.864
can block the interaction of the fusion protein and it can block the

241
00:13:53.884 --> 00:13:57.444
interaction of the splicing complex and cause exon skipping.

242
00:13:58.204 --> 00:14:02.024
Even more interesting, you can bring in this Cas13, which is

243
00:14:02.104 --> 00:14:05.264
coupled to a biotin ligase, and now you can

