ultimately are going to collapse a replication fork into a double-strand

500
00:27:19.260 --> 00:27:19.560
break.

501
00:27:21.500 --> 00:27:24.780
And this is how we've actually thought about lots of drugs.

502
00:27:24.960 --> 00:27:27.520
So PARP's really not special in this case.

503
00:27:27.900 --> 00:27:31.340
We put the BRCA pathway down below collapsed forks with many

504
00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:33.440
different genotoxic agents.

505
00:27:34.980 --> 00:27:38.620
And when it comes to BRCA1, it is known to actually promote homologous

506
00:27:38.630 --> 00:27:41.869
recombination indirectly by opposing this

507
00:27:41.960 --> 00:27:45.580
anti-resection factor, 53BP1. So in the

508
00:27:45.660 --> 00:27:49.040
absence of BRCA1, the cell killing goes through

509
00:27:49.200 --> 00:27:50.180
53BP1.

510
00:27:51.700 --> 00:27:55.280
And so if you now get rid of 53BP1, you restore

511
00:27:55.320 --> 00:27:58.120
resistance, or you restore homologous recombination.

512
00:27:58.160 --> 00:28:02.080
But actually, you get very strong PARP inhibitor resistance, but not resistance

513
00:28:02.100 --> 00:28:05.860
to all of the drugs that are supposed to work through this model, like

514
00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:07.800
Cisplatin. You do not get resistance to that.

515
00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:10.060
So a little bit confusing how this works.

516
00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:15.260
Furthermore, when people started to look at DNA replication doing these DNA fiber

517
00:28:15.320 --> 00:28:19.149
type assays, what they saw is that when they treated cells with a drug such as a

518
00:28:19.180 --> 00:28:23.160
PARP inhibitor, replication didn't pause or collapse or

519
00:28:23.180 --> 00:28:25.820
even pause. In fact, things went faster.

520
00:28:26.780 --> 00:28:30.110
And so now it's really confusing. How do we get this double-strand break that we're

521
00:28:30.120 --> 00:28:32.180
supposed to have when the forks collapse?

522
00:28:33.180 --> 00:28:37.080
And so what was postulated is that if you go too fast, you break the speed

523
00:28:37.160 --> 00:28:39.260
limit, and this gives you the double-strand break.

524
00:28:40.900 --> 00:28:41.600
So in the end,

525
00:28:42.620 --> 00:28:45.120
it's a bit complicated, the double-strand break model.

526
00:28:45.240 --> 00:28:47.240
Lots of concessions had to be made.

527
00:28:47.520 --> 00:28:51.260
And then when we see in the clinic that PARP inhibitors are sometimes working, even

528
00:28:51.280 --> 00:28:54.370
when there isn't an HRD, and sometimes they're not working.

529
00:28:54.460 --> 00:28:56.699
So it's been a little bit of a challenge.

530
00:28:57.760 --> 00:29:00.620
So what actually could explain BRCA-ness?

531
00:29:01.520 --> 00:29:05.180
So this is where we in the field have been looking at another function for the

532
00:29:05.220 --> 00:29:08.640
BRCA proteins, and that is in suppressing DNA

533
00:29:08.720 --> 00:29:10.060
replication gaps.

534
00:29:11.650 --> 00:29:15.600
And so the reason we got so excited about this particular function is that when we

535
00:29:15.700 --> 00:29:19.620
looked at our cancer cell line models that we had that were well-characterized, we

536
00:29:19.660 --> 00:29:23.420
could see that the HR and the fork protection functions, they didn't

537
00:29:23.500 --> 00:29:27.440
line up with therapy response. Whereas when you saw

538
00:29:27.560 --> 00:29:30.100
the gaps, when they were present,

539
00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:34.440
there was sensitivity. When the gaps were gone, there was resistance.

540
00:29:35.900 --> 00:29:36.580
And so that

541
00:29:37.460 --> 00:29:41.360
gave us some sense that this was important, at least for a biomarker, if

542
00:29:41.380 --> 00:29:44.980
anything. But we also looked at RAD51 foci more

543
00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:48.870
recently across these models, and that also didn't line up, and

544
00:29:48.900 --> 00:29:51.040
that's something, of course, that's being used clinically.

545
00:29:52.740 --> 00:29:55.300
And so an important thing to go back to then, of course, is this

546
00:29:55.320 --> 00:29:58.980
BRCA1-deficient cell system. Again, when you

547
00:29:59.440 --> 00:30:02.160
remove 53BP1, you restore homologous recombination.

548
00:30:02.480 --> 00:30:05.200
But what we had found is it also suppresses gaps.

549
00:30:06.900 --> 00:30:10.080
So then you don't really know what's driving the resistance in this case.

550
00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:13.980
And what Jos Jonkers' group went on to do is to do a screen and look how you can

551
00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:17.980
resensitize these double knockout cells to a PARP inhibitor.

552
00:30:18.220 --> 00:30:21.040
And what he found is that ligase III loss did that.

553
00:30:21.710 --> 00:30:25.079
And in his study, he found that gaps came back, but homologous

554
00:30:25.100 --> 00:30:28.800
recombination remained intact. So again, suggesting that

555
00:30:29.300 --> 00:30:33.196
gaps were quite important here.And so then moving on

556
00:30:33.276 --> 00:30:37.176
to thinking, we're being fairly encouraged by this data.

557
00:30:37.196 --> 00:30:40.876
We went on to think about how we could expand this model and suggest that

558
00:30:40.936 --> 00:30:44.036
it was what's driving the DDR reactions and synthetic

559
00:30:44.076 --> 00:30:46.696
lethalities that we had been working with.

560
00:30:47.576 --> 00:30:51.536
And indeed, Alan D'Andrea has been working in this area as well and showing

561
00:30:51.546 --> 00:30:55.096
PARP inhibitors, USP1 inhibitors, are also driving a gap

562
00:30:55.136 --> 00:30:55.776
phenotype.

563
00:30:57.306 --> 00:31:01.136
And so then coming together, if gaps align with response and drugs

564
00:31:01.176 --> 00:31:05.156
exploit these gaps, now why are we still focused on double-strand breaks

565
00:31:05.196 --> 00:31:05.916
and HRD?

566
00:31:07.696 --> 00:31:11.656
Well, we'd realized these genes are called HR genes, so it's going to be

567
00:31:11.716 --> 00:31:15.396
hard to take that apart. And we have really well-established

568
00:31:15.436 --> 00:31:17.416
double-strand break and HRD assays.

569
00:31:18.796 --> 00:31:21.056
The molecular basis of gaps is not clear.

570
00:31:22.056 --> 00:31:25.025
And the gap detection assays are really time-consuming.

571
00:31:25.096 --> 00:31:26.756
They're not clinically actionable.

572
00:31:26.796 --> 00:31:30.345
If people have done DNA fiber assays, they're probably wishing they

573
00:31:30.376 --> 00:31:31.136
hadn't.

574
00:31:33.016 --> 00:31:34.496
So what I want to talk about today

575
00:31:35.716 --> 00:31:38.756
are two stories. One is where Hitha,

576
00:31:39.616 --> 00:31:43.286
an outstanding, talented postdoc, has now tried to define the molecular

577
00:31:43.376 --> 00:31:44.536
basis of these gaps.

578
00:31:45.516 --> 00:31:49.436
And then Jenna Whelan, who's here, has been developing a tool to

579
00:31:49.476 --> 00:31:52.996
detect gaps, and she has a poster about that on Wednesday as well.

580
00:31:54.756 --> 00:31:55.996
And so we had proposed

581
00:31:57.076 --> 00:32:00.936
several years ago now that BRCA is working in parallel with PARP

582
00:32:01.496 --> 00:32:05.336
to suppress replication gaps. And this came following Keith

583
00:32:05.376 --> 00:32:08.756
Caldecott's work proposing that PARP is also

584
00:32:08.796 --> 00:32:12.476
functioning in replication in unperturbed cells in the

585
00:32:12.756 --> 00:32:13.996
lagging strand processing.

586
00:32:15.396 --> 00:32:16.156
Now, this model

587
00:32:17.396 --> 00:32:20.836
was supported in some ways, but we really didn't know why

588
00:32:20.916 --> 00:32:21.776
BRCA1

589
00:32:23.116 --> 00:32:26.556
was required to suppress 53BP1 to prevent these gaps.

590
00:32:27.616 --> 00:32:31.116
And so we had to figure out how does 53BP1 fit into this space, and it is best

591
00:32:31.196 --> 00:32:34.606
known for its role in double-strand break repair, but not really at the

592
00:32:34.676 --> 00:32:37.216
replication fork. Now, a few years ago,

593
00:32:38.236 --> 00:32:42.115
Steven Wagner's group showed that actually 53BP1 is an RNA-binding protein

594
00:32:42.136 --> 00:32:44.536
that binds the lagging strand flap.

595
00:32:45.476 --> 00:32:46.976
So that was a really important finding.

596
00:32:47.516 --> 00:32:51.256
And so we started to think, well, is this how 53BP1 relates to

597
00:32:51.316 --> 00:32:54.316
BRCA1 with respect to replication gaps?

598
00:32:55.556 --> 00:32:59.416
And so in this work, they had shown that FEN1 inhibitors could be

599
00:32:59.556 --> 00:33:02.276
used to show that 53BP1 was on the flap.

600
00:33:02.736 --> 00:33:05.976
So using the assays like they did, these sort of PLA

601
00:33:06.956 --> 00:33:10.936
or SURF assays, now we're looking at whether 53BP1

602
00:33:10.976 --> 00:33:13.896
is on nascent DNA, which is labeled with Edu.

603
00:33:14.656 --> 00:33:17.996
And using a FEN1 inhibitor, we could also see that we got more

604
00:33:18.136 --> 00:33:20.096
53BP1 with nascent DNA

605
00:33:21.716 --> 00:33:22.956
following a FEN1 inhibitor.

606
00:33:24.736 --> 00:33:28.456
So then looking at a BRCA1 knockout cell from Dan

607
00:33:28.476 --> 00:33:29.416
Durocher's group,

608
00:33:30.276 --> 00:33:34.216
we could also see that 53BP1 was accumulating on this nascent

609
00:33:34.256 --> 00:33:37.996
DNA in the absence of BRCA1, and that signal was fully

610
00:33:38.036 --> 00:33:39.666
dependent on 53BP1.

611
00:33:41.116 --> 00:33:44.956
Likewise, cells where BRCA1 had been complemented back dropped the

612
00:33:45.016 --> 00:33:47.576
signal in a cancer cell line.

613
00:33:48.876 --> 00:33:52.596
And so we didn't have any way to understand how BRCA1 might

614
00:33:52.996 --> 00:33:56.676
actually process the flap, so we thought maybe it works through FEN1.

615
00:33:58.576 --> 00:34:02.196
And so here now we have to ask the question: Does BRCA1 do

616
00:34:02.276 --> 00:34:03.376
anything to FEN1?

617
00:34:04.296 --> 00:34:07.096
And here we developed the same kind of assay where now we're going to do that

618
00:34:07.136 --> 00:34:09.877
proximity assay with FEN1 and nascent DNA.

619
00:34:10.397 --> 00:34:14.036
But in addition to the pulse, we're also going to add a chase here to see

620
00:34:14.076 --> 00:34:18.016
when FEN1 is at the fork, when does it accumulate the most,

621
00:34:18.136 --> 00:34:21.836
and when does it actually complete its association with nascent DNA.

622
00:34:23.676 --> 00:34:26.377
And so what we found here in these sort of wild-type cells,

623
00:34:27.296 --> 00:34:31.116
that FEN1 was here at the fork, but it accumulated just behind the

624
00:34:31.256 --> 00:34:31.556
fork,

625
00:34:32.556 --> 00:34:36.176
and then it rapidly dropped off, pretty much gone by 20 minutes.

626
00:34:37.996 --> 00:34:41.056
And so what about BRCA1 loss? What does that do to FEN1?

627
00:34:41.937 --> 00:34:45.616
So here it was quite interesting. We could see that FEN1 seemed to sort of get

628
00:34:45.736 --> 00:34:49.636
stuck at the active fork, drop dramatically, and then come

629
00:34:49.716 --> 00:34:52.136
back up like it was trying again behind the fork.

630
00:34:52.796 --> 00:34:56.556
Saw this shift to the active fork in other BRCA mutant cell

631
00:34:56.616 --> 00:34:56.937
lines.

632
00:34:58.436 --> 00:34:59.736
So this is what this might look like.

633
00:34:59.776 --> 00:35:01.376
In the absence of BRCA1, they're sort of

634
00:35:02.416 --> 00:35:06.396
getting stuck up here, dropping, and then coming back later to try to process

635
00:35:06.416 --> 00:35:06.936
the flap.

636
00:35:08.796 --> 00:35:11.096
Okay, so these are synthetic lethal partners.

637
00:35:11.476 --> 00:35:14.216
Does PARP also play a role in positioning FEN1?

638
00:35:15.916 --> 00:35:18.356
So now we're going to do the same experiment.

639
00:35:18.436 --> 00:35:21.976
So now we're going to look in the presence and the absence of PARP1.

640
00:35:22.856 --> 00:35:26.486
And what we can see here is that in the absence of PARP1, we also see this

641
00:35:26.516 --> 00:35:29.756
shift to the active fork, a dropping, and then a

642
00:35:29.796 --> 00:35:32.156
re-accumulation further behind the fork.

643
00:35:33.716 --> 00:35:36.476
And this generally mimicked what we saw with BRCA loss.

644
00:35:37.376 --> 00:35:40.276
So we would argue that BRCA1 or PARP loss

645
00:35:41.216 --> 00:35:42.716
give a similar kind of

646
00:35:43.556 --> 00:35:44.316
phenotype here.

647
00:35:46.136 --> 00:35:48.296
Okay. So now what happens if we get rid of both?

648
00:35:49.236 --> 00:35:51.996
Is this relevant to the synthetic lethality?

649
00:35:52.856 --> 00:35:56.436
So now we take a BRCA1-deficient cell, and we use a PARP

650
00:35:56.456 --> 00:36:00.216
inhibitor, and we see something quite dramatic, and that is that there isn't really

651
00:36:00.256 --> 00:36:02.476
any FEN1 making it to behind the fork.

652
00:36:02.876 --> 00:36:05.496
Seems like everything is stacked up here at the fork.

653
00:36:07.276 --> 00:36:08.616
And so what does that look like?

654
00:36:09.816 --> 00:36:12.176
So this is what we would sort of draw this to look like.

655
00:36:13.176 --> 00:36:16.576
Okay, so if this is relevant to synthetic lethality, then

656
00:36:16.716 --> 00:36:19.156
53BP1 should affect this outcome.

657
00:36:20.796 --> 00:36:24.336
And so what I showed you before in BRCA1-deficient cells, 53BP1 is

658
00:36:24.376 --> 00:36:25.096
accumulating

659
00:36:25.896 --> 00:36:29.476
at the flap. And so we could imagine then if we got rid of

660
00:36:29.516 --> 00:36:33.496
53BP1 in these cells, they might start to look like a wild-type

661
00:36:33.576 --> 00:36:37.566
cell, and that would explain why they're more resistant to a PARP inhibitor and

662
00:36:37.576 --> 00:36:41.428
a FEN1 inhibitor and so forth.But this is where we

663
00:36:41.488 --> 00:36:45.028
were very wrong. So looking at the double knockout cells,

664
00:36:45.708 --> 00:36:47.168
FEN1 seemed to go away.

665
00:36:51.208 --> 00:36:52.808
And so that was quite dramatic.

666
00:36:53.708 --> 00:36:57.648
And we also looked in the 50BP1 single knockout cells, and

667
00:36:58.168 --> 00:36:59.448
FEN1 was also dropping.

668
00:37:01.348 --> 00:37:04.868
And so what Keith Caldecott has described is that the canonical

669
00:37:04.878 --> 00:37:08.798
pathway, if it's not doing its job properly, PARP can

670
00:37:08.868 --> 00:37:11.808
actually come to the rescue and sort of do a backup.

671
00:37:11.948 --> 00:37:13.808
So we wondered if that was what was going on here.

672
00:37:14.308 --> 00:37:15.688
And so now we want to look at PARP.

673
00:37:16.648 --> 00:37:20.228
And so we can see that PARP was at the active fork in a wild-type cell.

674
00:37:20.748 --> 00:37:24.708
If you lose BRCA1, you actually get more PARP1 at the active fork, and it seems

675
00:37:24.728 --> 00:37:27.828
to persist behind the fork. If you now lose

676
00:37:27.988 --> 00:37:31.068
50BP1, indeed, PARP does go up quite

677
00:37:31.108 --> 00:37:33.128
dramatically at the active fork.

678
00:37:34.568 --> 00:37:37.508
But the question really then became, well, is this PARP active?

679
00:37:38.428 --> 00:37:42.208
Okay, so now we're going to do an antibody to the PAR activity.

680
00:37:43.118 --> 00:37:46.848
And what we see is that there's more PAR activity in the BRCA1 knockout cells,

681
00:37:47.208 --> 00:37:50.828
but this drops very much so when you get rid of 50BP1.

682
00:37:51.448 --> 00:37:55.008
Likewise, in a 50BP1 knockout cell, we see low PAR

683
00:37:55.108 --> 00:37:57.228
activity at the replication fork.

684
00:37:58.708 --> 00:38:02.568
Okay, so that allows us then to put 50BP1 actually in a PARP pathway

685
00:38:03.128 --> 00:38:06.768
being required for PARP activity and FEN1 positioning.

686
00:38:07.368 --> 00:38:11.208
Now, if I fold this around and then put 50BP1 back on the flap, it would

687
00:38:11.228 --> 00:38:15.028
look something like this. We have two pathways that are positioning

688
00:38:15.068 --> 00:38:18.968
FEN1 at the replication fork, directed by 50BP1 through the

689
00:38:19.008 --> 00:38:22.158
PARP, and then a separate one that BRCA1 is directing.

690
00:38:23.678 --> 00:38:27.628
So how does that then play out? Well, what we think is that here you

691
00:38:27.788 --> 00:38:31.658
have rapid and efficient lagging strand maturation with

692
00:38:31.668 --> 00:38:35.048
these two pathways working together in a

693
00:38:35.068 --> 00:38:38.528
coordinated manner. Now, if you lose BRCA1,

694
00:38:39.528 --> 00:38:43.448
what you start to see is PARP working overtime because you're

695
00:38:43.468 --> 00:38:46.988
not completing the task here. You have to come in later and kind of do

696
00:38:47.068 --> 00:38:49.088
repeated attempts at this processing.

697
00:38:49.508 --> 00:38:52.148
So it's a delayed and inefficient maturation.

698
00:38:54.188 --> 00:38:57.988
And this is what we believe is causing high sensitivity then to

699
00:38:58.028 --> 00:39:01.488
PARP inhibitors, because now you have lots of PARP activity to target.

700
00:39:04.168 --> 00:39:08.008
So now when you lose 50BP1, you

701
00:39:08.048 --> 00:39:12.028
don't have the BRCA1 positioning pathway, and you don't have the PARP

702
00:39:12.048 --> 00:39:14.117
positioning pathway. So what happens?

703
00:39:14.308 --> 00:39:15.768
FEN1 is disengaged,

704
00:39:16.988 --> 00:39:20.738
and PARP is inactive. So this would explain why

705
00:39:20.808 --> 00:39:23.188
you're not sensitive to a PARP inhibitor.

706
00:39:23.208 --> 00:39:26.848
PARP's not active, and you're not sensitive to a FEN1 inhibitor because

707
00:39:26.888 --> 00:39:29.228
FEN1 is not even at the replisome.

708
00:39:30.808 --> 00:39:34.448
So this would argue it's about target loss, not restoration of DNA

709
00:39:34.488 --> 00:39:35.008
repair.

710
00:39:37.188 --> 00:39:40.788
So what can we do with this for biomarker identity?

711
00:39:40.908 --> 00:39:43.708
So here in these cells, there's a lot going on.

712
00:39:43.897 --> 00:39:47.068
So is there anything here we can use as a biomarker of

713
00:39:47.128 --> 00:39:48.828
sensitivity to different drugs?

714
00:39:50.528 --> 00:39:53.288
And so we thought, well, maturation is problematic here.

715
00:39:54.388 --> 00:39:58.318
And so maturation actually can be looked at, as Beng Shen has

716
00:39:58.408 --> 00:40:00.888
shown, by doing a nick translation assay.

717
00:40:01.808 --> 00:40:05.748
So what he had shown is in a FEN1 knockout cell, you get these nicks or

718
00:40:05.848 --> 00:40:09.728
gaps behind the fork, and you can do a nick translation assay, where you're

719
00:40:09.748 --> 00:40:13.638
actually including-- now you're adding some BrdU, and you can come in with an

720
00:40:13.648 --> 00:40:17.348
antibody to see that. And sure enough, we can also see with a FEN1

721
00:40:17.388 --> 00:40:18.888
inhibitor, this signal goes up.

722
00:40:20.388 --> 00:40:24.068
So now if you put this FEN1 inhibitor on a BRCA1 deficient cell, the

723
00:40:24.108 --> 00:40:26.208
signal goes up quite a bit more,

724
00:40:27.248 --> 00:40:31.138
okay? Suggesting, again, FEN1 is working very hard in these cells, and

725
00:40:31.168 --> 00:40:34.228
it's very important to the maturation of the lagging strand.

726
00:40:35.008 --> 00:40:38.868
Now, if you put the same FEN1 inhibitor on the double knockout cells where 50BP1

727
00:40:38.908 --> 00:40:41.648
is not there, we don't see any effect.

728
00:40:42.048 --> 00:40:45.248
So FEN1 inhibitor in the endogenous, no treatment

729
00:40:45.928 --> 00:40:49.448
without 50B1 binding. 50BP1,

730
00:40:49.528 --> 00:40:53.228
BRCA1, there's very little signal to start with, and then the inhibitor doesn't do

731
00:40:53.268 --> 00:40:53.638
anything.

732
00:40:54.588 --> 00:40:58.348
So this made us think, well, maybe we can just look at

733
00:40:59.268 --> 00:41:02.208
the maturation as a biomarker of

734
00:41:03.308 --> 00:41:04.528
this kind of sensitivity.

735
00:41:05.488 --> 00:41:09.248
So can we use this nick translation or gaps or

736
00:41:09.668 --> 00:41:13.648
failed maturation for a biomarker of response without

737
00:41:13.688 --> 00:41:15.208
even adding any DNA damage?

